ast Germany’s ruling party never officially acknowledged responsibility for the crimes committed in Germany’s name during the Third Reich. Instead, it cast communists as both victims of and victors over National Socialist oppression while marginalizing discussions of Jewish suffering. Yet for the 1977 Academy Awards, the Ministry of Culture submitted Jakob der Lügner – a film focused exclusively on Jewish victimhood that would become the only East German film to ever be officially nominated. By combining close analyses of key films with extensive archival research, this book explores how GDR filmmakers depicted Jews and the Holocaust in a country where memories of Nazi persecution were highly prescribed, tightly controlled and invariably political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszGermany (East)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  a1977 academy awards.  aantifascist resistance.  aantifascist.  aantisemitic.  aarchival research.  aberlin.  abilder des zeugen.  acinema.  acommunist.  acrime.  aeast german film and the holocaust.  aeast germany.  aengaging.  aeurope.  aeuropean history.  afilm studies.  agdr filmmakers.  agdr.  agermany.  agood and evil.  agovernment and governing.  aholocaust.  ajakob der lugner.  ajewish suffering.  ajewish victimhood.  ajewish.  amarginalizing discussions.  anational socialist oppression.  anazi persecution.  apage turner.  arealistic.  asocialist oppression.  athird reich.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311099767540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789207484?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789207484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cove